                        <provenance type="found" when="1891">Discovered lying in the graveyard. According to Macalister (1945, 40) these ogham stones were first discovered and mentioned in 1891 by Shelley. Barry (1896, 122) notes that he first heard of these ogham stones from Rev. Denis Murphy in 1891 and then again in 1892 from Mr. John Cummins. Barry visited the site and saw the stones in 1892 and again in 1893, when photographs were taken of both ogham stones standing upright. This stone was discovered first, shortly followed by the second (I-KIK-011), which stood marking a modern grave nearby.</provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed" when="2020">On site in the position in which it was discovered, lying in the graveyard. Both stones were recorded in 3d (in collaboration with Digital Heritage Age) in June 2020 as an action of the County Kilkenny Heritage Plan Programme, funded by the Heritage Office of Kilkenny County Council and the Heritage Council.</provenance>
